we have a philosophical problem here (I don't say it's wrong)
2^0 = 1
Whoever opts for binary decimal conversion will have to treat this as a particular case.

const s = readline();
const n = parseInt(readline());
let len = 2**n;
let zeros = "0".repeat(n);
let regex = new RegExp(`${s}`,"gi");
let q = 0;
for(let i = 0; i < len; i++){
    q += ((zeros+i.toString(2)).slice(-n).match(regex) || []).length > 0;
}
print(n ? q/len : 0); // n == 0 it is a particular case
